Additionally, photoinduced electron-hole pair separation and transfer may be effectively seen using electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS), and the prevalent view is that the charge transfer resistance increases with arc radius [62] . Fig. 16
(a) shows the EIS Nyquist plots of GCN and CDCN NCs. When CDCN is compared to GCN, a significantly smaller arc radius is seen, suggesting quicker charge transfer kinetics at the interface between the electrode and the electrolyte. The sensitization of GCNwith CDCNlowers theresistance to charge transfer (Rct) and increases photocatalytic activity, as catalytic activity is inversely related to Rct. The developed composite's chargerecombination and charge transfer efficiencies were further investigated by analysing the GCNand CDCN nanocompositePL spectra at a 335 nm excitation wavelength. Photoluminescence (PL) experiments assessed the excitonic performances of the synthesized samples. Fluorescence occurs mainly by the electromagnetic decay of singlet excitons, with the intensity of PL reflecting the concentration of these excitons [63]. Fig. 16(b) shows that CDCNhas amuch lower Photoluminescenceintensity (PL)compared to pristine GCN.Compounds with low intensity in the spectrum of PL possess a small recombination rate for photogenerated charge carriers. The results of Fig. 15(b) show that CDCNimproves chargecarrier separation by preventing electron and hole recombination, leading to increased photocatalytic efficiency. The production of reactive oxygen species (ROS) over the CDCN nanocompositeunder UV light irradiation was investigated using a DMPO spin-trapping EPR approach in order better understand inthe dye degradation (CM/IC)mechanism by the CDCNcomposite (Fig. 16 (c–d). The EPR study reveals the critical roles of both hydroxyl (
OH) and superoxide (O2
) radicals in the photocatalytic degradation of CM/IC dye. Under UV light irradiation, a strong EPR signal for
OH and less intensity of (O2
) radicals are observed, indicating their significant contribution to the degradation process. On the other hand, in the absence of light, no significantsignal was observed suggesting that the formation of
OH and (O2
) radicals is not possible in the dark condition. These results were aligned with the proposed photocatalytic mechanism, wherein light excitation of the catalyst generates electron-hole pairs, with the holes facilitating the production of radicles.
